<h2>Synergy Matrix: Who Does What</h2>

<p>The beauty of this stack is that almost every critical healing mechanism is covered by at least two of the three peptides. That redundancy matters. If one compound underperforms in a given tissue type, another picks up the slack.</p>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Healing Mechanism</th><th>BPC-157</th><th>TB-500</th><th>GHK-Cu</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>Angiogenesis</strong></td><td class="g">Strong</td><td class="g">Strong</td><td class="y">Moderate</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Collagen synthesis</strong></td><td class="g">Strong</td><td class="y">Indirect</td><td class="g">Strong</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Stem cell recruitment</strong></td><td class="y">Moderate</td><td class="g">Strong</td><td class="g">Strong</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Inflammation control</strong></td><td class="g">Strong</td><td class="g">Strong</td><td class="g">Strong</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Antioxidant effects</strong></td><td class="r">Minimal</td><td class="r">Minimal</td><td class="g">Strong</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Nerve regeneration</strong></td><td class="g">Strong</td><td class="y">Moderate</td><td class="r">Minimal</td></tr>
